INSTALL — IRCIT 0.3.1
=======================

Dependencies
------------

Required:
  - GCC or Clang — IRCIT uses GNU C extensions (__attribute__, statement
    expressions) which both GCC and Clang support.
  - CMake >= 3.10
  - Ncurses — a compatible static build of ncurses 5.2 is vendored under
    packages/ncurses-5.2/ and used by default. No system ncurses needed.

Optional (for system ncurses fallback):
  - System ncurses development headers and library. Pass
    -DFORCE_SYSTEM_NCURSES=ON to cmake to use the system ncurses instead
    of the vendored one. Note that modern ncurses 6.x may expose ABI
    differences that prevent compilation — the vendored 5.2 is the safe path.


Build Instructions
------------------

1. Create a build directory (out-of-tree build):

       mkdir build && cd build

2. Configure:

       cmake .. -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Debug

   For a release build, use -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=Release.

   To use system ncurses instead of the vendored one:

       cmake .. -DFORCE_SYSTEM_NCURSES=ON

   To point at a different ncurses installation:

       cmake .. -DNCURSES_PREFIX=/path/to/ncurses

3. Build:

       cmake --build . -j$(nproc)

4. The binary is at ./ircit. Verify it works:

       ./ircit -v


Installation
------------

To install config files and the man page:

       cmake --build . --target install

This will:
  - Copy etc/ircit.conf and etc/ircit.fpl to ~/.ircit/ (only if not
    already present — existing files are never overwritten).
  - Install doc/ircit.1 to share/man/man1/.

The ircit binary itself is not installed to a system path by default.
Copy it to your preferred bin directory manually:

       cp ircit ~/bin/   # or /usr/local/bin/


Troubleshooting
---------------

Compilation fails with "macro names must be identifiers" or similar:
  The vendored ncurses 5.2 was not found. Ensure
  packages/ncurses-5.2/lib/libncurses.a exists. If missing, re-run the
  ncurses 5.2 build or use -DFORCE_SYSTEM_NCURSES=ON.

Linker errors about multiple definitions:
  Ensure cmake is adding -fcommon and -fgnu89-inline to the compile
  flags. These are set automatically by the CMakeLists.txt.

Compiler complains about GNU extensions:
  Ensure you are using GCC or Clang. Other compilers (MSVC, ICC classic)
  may not support the GNU C extensions used throughout the codebase.

       export CC=gcc    # or: export CC=clang
